, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England"},"cs":{"1389–26 October 1452":"1389–26. října 1452","1393–1451":"1393–1451","1451–1511":"1451–1511","1389–1452":"1389–1452","5 August 1451":"5. srpna 1451","1511":"1511","1389":"1389","1452":"1452","1451":"1451","26 October 1452":"26. října 1452","1393":"1393","Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Staffordshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Anglie","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Anglie"},"da":{"1389–26 October 1452":"1389–26. oktober 1452","1393–1451":"1393–1451","1451–1511":"1451–1511","1389–1452":"1389–1452","5 August 1451":"5. august 1451","1511":"1511","1389":"1389","1452":"1452","1451":"1451","26 October 1452":"26. oktober 1452","1393":"1393","Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England"},"nl":{"1389–26 October 1452":"1389–26 oktober 1452","1393–1451":"1393–1451","1451–1511":"1451–1511","1389–1452":"1389–1452","5 August 1451":"5 augustus 1451","1511":"1511","1389":"1389","1452":"1452","1451":"1451","26 October 1452":"26 oktober 1452","1393":"1393","Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England"},"en":{"1389–26 October 1452":"1389–26 October 1452","1393–1451":"1393–1451","1451–1511":"1451–1511","1389–1452":"1389–1452","5 August 1451":"5 August 1451","1511":"1511","1389":"1389","1452":"1452","1451":"1451","26 October 1452":"26 October 1452","1393":"1393","Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Milton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from one or other of the many places called Milton, or sometimes Middleton (see   Middleton  ) and occasionally Melton (see   Melton  ), most of which derive from Old English <i>middel</i> ‘middle’ or <i>myln</i> ‘mill’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Middleton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places so called. In over thirty instances from many different areas, the name is from Old English <i>midel</i> ‘middle’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. However, Middleton on the Hill near Leominster in Herefordshire appears in Domesday Book as <i>Miceltune</i>, the first element clearly being Old English <i>micel</i> ‘large’, ‘great’ (see   Middlebrook  ). Middleton Baggot and Middleton Priors in Shropshire have early spellings that suggest <i>gem̄thhyll</i> (from <i>gem̄th</i> ‘confluence’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’) + <i>tūn</i> as the origin. This surname is also found in Scotland and Ireland.","History: A Scottish family of this name derives it from lands at Middleto(u)n near Kincardine. The Scottish physician Peter Middleton practiced in New York City after 1752 and was one of the founders of the medical school at King's College (now Columbia University) in 1767. One of the earliest of the Charleston, SC, Middleton family of prominent legislators was Arthur Middleton, born in Charleston in 1681. The name has also been established in Ireland since at least the 13th century; its presence was reinforced by settlers in the 17th century."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Lord Richard Milton was born in 1389, in Staffordshire, England. He had at least 1 daughter with Margaret De Pershale. He died on 26 October 1452, in his hometown, at the age of 63."},"et":{"1389–26 October 1452":"1389–26. oktoober 1452","1393–1451":"1393–1451","1451–1511":"1451–1511","1389–1452":"1389–1452","5 August 1451":"5. august 1451","1511":"1511","1389":"1389","1452":"1452","1451":"1451","26 October 1452":"26. oktoober 1452","1393":"1393","Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England"},"fi":{"1389–26 October 1452":"1389–26. lokakuuta 1452","1393–1451":"1393–1451","1451–1511":"1451–1511","1389–1452":"1389–1452","5 August 1451":"5. elokuuta 1451","1511":"1511","1389":"1389","1452":"1452","1451":"1451","26 Oct